          "body": "The psalm's final verse is a question: 'Who is wise? Let him give heed to these things, and consider the lovingkindnesses of the LORD' (v.43). This closing move transforms the psalm from testimony to pedagogy. The four stories are not merely historical records; they are data for the wise to interpret. Wisdom (*chakhmah*) in the Hebrew tradition is the skill of reading reality correctly — of seeing what is actually happening behind the surface of events. The psalmist claims that the person who can look at lostness rescued, bondage broken, sickness healed, and storm stilled and recognize in all four the same chesed operative — that person is wise. Spurgeon noted that the psalm teaches us to read our own lives sapientially: 'Every mercy should be observed, every deliverance should be noted in our diary.' The wise reader of Psalm 107 is the reader who has learned to identify the 'then they cried' moments in their own history, to see which stanza is their story, and to add their testimony to the chorus of the redeemed."
